## 5. PARALLEL FETCHING

**Anti-pattern — request waterfall:**
```tsx
// BAD: sequential — second fetch waits for first
useEffect(() => {
  const fetchData = async () => {
    const users = await fetch('/api/users').then(r => r.json());
    const projects = await fetch('/api/projects').then(r => r.json());
    setData({ users, projects });
  };
  fetchData();
}, []);
```

**Correct — parallel fetching:**
```tsx
// GOOD: both requests fire simultaneously
useEffect(() => {
  const controller = new AbortController();

  const fetchData = async () => {
    try {
      const [users, projects] = await Promise.all([
        fetch('/api/users', { signal: controller.signal }).then(r => r.json()),
        fetch('/api/projects', { signal: controller.signal }).then(r => r.json()),
      ]);
      setData({ users, projects });
    } catch (err) {
      if (err instanceof DOMException && err.name === 'AbortError') return;
      setError(err instanceof Error ? err : new Error('Fetch failed'));
    }
  };

  fetchData();
  return () => controller.abort();
}, []);
```

**With React Query:**
```tsx
// Both queries fire in parallel automatically
const users = useQuery({ queryKey: ['users'], queryFn: fetchUsers });
const projects = useQuery({ queryKey: ['projects'], queryFn: fetchProjects });

const isLoading = users.isLoading || projects.isLoading;
const error = users.error || projects.error;
```

